values:
Ladies and gentlemen of the jury, I am up to my asshole in barely concealed FEAR.&nbsp; Let me make this clear to you all.&nbsp; I am clenching and shaking with both anticipation and nervousness.

I have met my worst enemy, and she has challenged me to a game of chess, and a gentlemanly game of it that I'm not sure I'm up for.&nbsp; She is a minister that I'm fond of on a friendship level.&nbsp; I don't want to offend her, and I certainly don't want to offend her congregation, but I still want to be definitive and positive with what I say.&nbsp; However, I am speaking in a church, which I have little respect for the teachings of, other than the simple respect for the 'goodliness' of it all.

I am an atheist, (I'm an ordained reverend and whatnot, capitalize 'atheist or 'reverend' if you need a title or whatever.&nbsp; I'm not particular) and as devout and pure and as clean of soul as any atheist can be, and I have been invited to talk to an actual church congregation about atheism!&nbsp; I mean shit!&nbsp; Baptist?&nbsp; Mennonite?&nbsp; Neither of which I know a whole lot about, or how they differ.&nbsp; Test of bloody courage in the slanderous eyes of your not-quite peers?&nbsp; I want to describe the ways that "atheists aren't 'evil".&nbsp; That is the intent of it, anyway.&nbsp; But you can't get a more dismissive,&nbsp; tougher audience, and I'm no public speaker!&nbsp; I have stage fright at picturing the the first word.&nbsp;
